# Windows build toolchain (MSVC only)

You are running on **Windows**. Before running any CMake, Ninja, or MSBuild
command that compiles the C++ engine, follow the mandatory pre-flight gate
below. MinGW silently breaks this build — read this rule before you run
`cmake` / `ninja`.

> Full guide: [docs/guidelines/windows_android_setup.md](../../docs/guidelines/windows_android_setup.md) §3.

## Pre-flight gate (run before any `cmake` or `ninja` command)

Answer these three questions **in order**. If any answer is "no", fix it
before proceeding — do not invoke CMake.

1. **Did this PowerShell session run `vcvars64.bat`?**
   - **No** → run this first, then continue:
     ```powershell
     & "C:\Program Files (x86)\Microsoft Visual Studio\2022\BuildTools\VC\Auxiliary\Build\vcvars64.bat"
     ```
   - If that path does not exist, locate it with:
     ```powershell
     Get-ChildItem -Recurse -Path "C:\Program Files (x86)\Microsoft Visual Studio", "C:\Program Files\Microsoft Visual Studio" -Filter vcvars64.bat
     ```
2. **Does `where cl.exe` return a path under MSVC's `VC\Tools\MSVC\…\bin\Hostx64\x64\?`**
   - **No** (returns `mingw`, `git\mingw64`, `msys`, `clang`, or `gcc`) →
     MinGW is still on PATH ahead of MSVC. Strip it with one of the recipes
     in [windows_android_setup.md](../../docs/guidelines/windows_android_setup.md) §13.1, then re-run `vcvars64.bat` and re-check.
3. **Is the build directory `build/engine-msvc/`?**
   - **No** → use `build/engine-msvc/`, **not** `build/engine/`. The
     latter is contaminated with a Linux GCC cache from prior sessions.
     Pick any non-default name if you want isolation from existing builds.

Only after all three are "yes" may you run `cmake -S engine_juce -B build/engine-msvc …`.

## Build / test commands (verified working)

```powershell
# Configure (MSVC + Ninja, C++20, tests on)
cmake -S engine_juce -B build/engine-msvc -G Ninja `
      -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Debug -DAUDIOAPP_BUILD_TESTS=ON

# Build the JUCE test runner
cmake --build build/engine-msvc --target audioapp_juce_tests

# Run all tests
.\build\engine-msvc\Debug\audioapp_juce_tests.exe

# Run a single test by name (substring match)
.\build\engine-msvc\Debug\audioapp_juce_tests.exe ClipLength

# List available tests
.\build\engine-msvc\Debug\audioapp_juce_tests.exe --list-tests
```

## Hard rules — never do these

- **Never** invoke `cmake` or `ninja` without `vcvars64.bat` first. CMake
  will silently pick `gcc` from a `mingw64\bin` on `PATH` and the build
  "succeeds" with the wrong toolchain, producing an `.lib` that the Android
  NDK's MSVC linker cannot consume.
- **Never** use `build/engine/` as the CMake build directory on Windows.
  It is contaminated with a Linux GCC cache; CMake will reuse the wrong
  compiler detection. Use `build/engine-msvc/` (or any non-default name).
- **Never** append `-DCMAKE_C_COMPILER=gcc -DCMAKE_CXX_COMPILER=g++` on
  Windows. That is the Linux build recipe. The Windows recipe lets
  `vcvars64.bat` set the compiler via `PATH` / `CC` / `CXX` env vars.
- **Never** try to build the engine with MinGW. JUCE 8 requires C++20
  features (e.g. `std::format`) that MinGW's libstdc++ lacks.

## Symptom → fix cheat sheet

If a build fails or CMake picks the wrong compiler, look up the symptom:

| Symptom | Cause | Fix |
|---------|-------|-----|
| `-- The C compiler identification is GNU` | MinGW on PATH | §13.1 (strip MinGW from PATH) |
| `error: 'std::format' is not a member of 'std'` | MinGW's libstdc++ lacks C++20 | §13.1 |
| `error: cannot find -lasound` on Windows | GCC picked up (ALSA is Linux) | §13.1 |
| `undefined reference to juce::*` linker errors | ABI mismatch (mixed MSVC + MinGW objects) | Delete `build/engine-msvc/`, rerun §3.1 + §3.3 |
| `cl.exe` not found after `vcvars64.bat` | Wrong VS install / non-default path | `Get-ChildItem -Recurse ... vcvars64.bat` |

Full recipes for stripping MinGW from PATH: [windows_android_setup.md](../../docs/guidelines/windows_android_setup.md) §13.1.

## Deploy to phone

After the engine tests are green and Flutter changes are ready:

```powershell
cd app_flutter
flutter build apk --debug -d ZY32MCWDJ6
adb -s ZY32MCWDJ6 install -r build\app\outputs\flutter-apk\app-debug.apk
```

Or use the wrapper scripts: `.\tools\flutter_deploy.ps1` and `.\tools\flutter_dev.ps1`. See §5 of the guide.

